SIMPLE: swingle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swingle
<hw>Swin"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Freq. of
<ets>swing</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dangle; to wave
hanging.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Johnson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To swing for pleasure.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swingle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swingle
<hw>Swin"gle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Swingled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swingling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See
<er>Swingel</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To clean, as flax, by beating
it with a swingle, so as to separate the coarse parts and the woody
substance from it; to scutch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To beat off the tops of without pulling up the
roots; -- said of weeds.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Forby.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swingle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Swingle
<hw>Swin"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A wooden instrument like a large
knife, about two feet long, with one thin edge, used for beating and
cleaning flax; a scutcher; -- called also <altname>swingling
knife</altname>, <altname>swingling staff</altname>, and
<altname>swingling wand</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<-- 2.  contraction for <it>swinging single</it>, i .e. an unmarried swinger[sense 3 or 4] [Colloq.] -->

<p><ent>Swinglebar</ent>⟦br⟧
